up|32|NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|My first thought was I am glad I did not double 3@H which I considered. It looks like we only have 4 tricks at best (2 diamonds and 2 hearts). The reason I did not double is because, although I had a lot of trump, they were all low and with partner's diamond raise we are not taking very many diamond tricks. So we probably have to take at least 3 tricks in spades and clubs which does not look likely with my hand.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now I have to decide how to take 10 tricks in diamonds. I only have 1 trick outside of diamonds although I might be able to set up a 2nd club trick.  I might be able to score 9 diamonds (assuming they don't figure out to lead diamonds) by ruffing 4 hearts in dummy. |
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But this presupposes that East, who is long in hearts, also has the @DJ. If West has the @DJ he will be able to ruff one of my hearts with the @DJ and I will end up losing 2 spades, 1 cub, and the @DJ.|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I started by leading a club so that I have club ruffs as entries to my hand to begin ruffing diamonds. Fortunately, the defense continues by cashing their spade winners, setting up my cross ruff. Once they try and cash a 2nd club, the cross ruff is set up, assuming East has the @DJ.|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Since luckily East has the @DJ, I end up taking my 10 tricks with the @HA, 4 heart ruffs in dummy, and 5 diamond tricks in my hand.|
